# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emi-filtering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] In electronics, a **choke** is an inductor used to block higher-frequency alternating currents (AC) while passing direct current (DC) and lower-frequency ACs in a circuit.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] A choke usually consists of a coil of insulated wire often wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a doughnut-shaped ferrite bead strung on a wire.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] The choke's impedance increases with frequency.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Its low electrical resistance passes both AC and DC with little power loss, but its reactance limits the amount of AC passed.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] The name comes from blocking—"choking"—high frequencies while passing low frequencies.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] It is a functional name; the name "choke" is used if an inductor is used for blocking or decoupling higher frequencies, but the component is simply called an "inductor" if used in electronic filters or tuned circuits.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Inductors designed for use as chokes are usually distinguished by not having low-loss construction (high Q factor) required in inductors used in tuned circuits and filtering applications.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Audio frequency chokes usually have ferromagnetic cores to increase their inductance.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] They are often constructed similarly to transformers, with laminated iron cores and an air gap.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] The iron core increases the inductance for a given volume of the core.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Chokes were frequently used in the design of rectifier power supplies for vacuum tube equipment such as radio receivers or amplifiers.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] They are commonly found in direct-current motor controllers to produce direct current (DC), where they were used in conjunction with large electrolytic capacitors to remove the voltage ripple (AC) at the output DC.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] A rectifier circuit designed for a choke-output filter may produce too much DC output voltage and subject the rectifier and filter capacitors to excessive in-rush and ripple currents if the inductor is removed.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] However, modern electrolytic capacitors with high ripple current ratings, and voltage regulators that remove more power supply ripple than chokes could, have eliminated heavy, bulky chokes from mains frequency power supplies.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Smaller chokes are used in switching power supplies to remove the higher-frequency switching transients from the output and sometimes from feeding back into the mains input.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Some car audio hobbyists use choke coils with automobile audio systems (specifically in the wiring of a subwoofer, to remove high frequencies from the amplified signal).
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Radio frequency chokes (RFC) often have iron powder or ferrite cores which increases inductance and overall operation.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] They are often wound in complex patterns (basket winding) to reduce self-capacitance and proximity effect losses.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Chokes for even higher frequencies have non-magnetic cores and low inductance.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] A modern form of choke used for eliminating digital RF noise from lines is the ferrite bead, a cylindrical or torus-shaped core of ferrite slipped over a wire.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] These are often seen on computer cables.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] A common-mode (CM) choke is a special application where a choke is used to act upon a common-mode signal.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] These chokes are useful for suppression of electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI) frequently introduced on high current wires such as on power supply lines, which may cause unwanted operation.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Reducing this noise is frequently done by using a common mode choke—two parallel coil windings on a single core.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Common mode chokes allow differential currents to pass while blocking signals that are affecting both wires.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Because the magnetic flux produced by differential-mode currents in the core of a common mode choke tend to cancel each other out, the choke presents little impedance to differential mode currents.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] It achieves this by the placement of windings such that they generate equal but opposite fields that cancel each other out for differential mode signals.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] Normally this also means that the core will not saturate for large differential mode currents, and the maximum current rating is instead determined by the heating effect of the winding resistance.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] On the other hand, common mode currents see a high impedance path due to the combined inductance of the windings that reinforce each other.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] CM chokes are commonly used in industrial, electrical and telecommunications applications to remove or decrease noise and related electromagnetic interference.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] When the CM choke is conducting CM current, most of the magnetic flux generated by the windings is confined within the inductor core because of its high permeability.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] In this case, the leakage flux, which is also the near magnetic field emission of the CM choke is low.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] However, the DM current flowing through the windings will generate high emitted near magnetic field since the windings are negative coupled in this case.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] To reduce the near magnetic field emission, a twisted winding structure can be applied to the CM choke.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] The difference between the balanced twisted windings CM choke and conventional balanced two winding CM choke is that the windings interact in the center of the core open window.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] When it is conducting CM current, the balanced twisted winding CM inductor can provide identical CM inductance as the conventional CM inductor.
[src:emi-filtering/common-mode-choke] When it is conducting DM current, the equivalent current loops will generate inversed direction magnetic fields in space so that they tend to cancel each other.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] In electrical engineering, **electromagnetic shielding** is the practice of reducing or redirecting the electromagnetic field (EMF) in a space with barriers made of conductive or magnetic materials.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] It is typically applied to enclosures, for isolating electrical devices from their surroundings, and to cables to isolate wires from the environment through which the cable runs ().
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic shielding that blocks radio frequency (RF) electromagnetic radiation is also known as **RF shielding**.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Practical field measurements in residential bedrooms typically use consumer EMF meters to determine local exposure levels.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] EMF shielding serves to minimize electromagnetic interference.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The shielding can reduce the coupling of radio waves, electromagnetic fields, and electrostatic fields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] A conductive enclosure used to block electrostatic fields is also known as a *Faraday cage*.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The amount of reduction depends very much upon the material used, its thickness, the size of the shielded volume and the frequency of the fields of interest and the size, shape and orientation of holes in a shield to an incident electromagnetic field.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Typical materials used for electromagnetic shielding include thin layer of metal, sheet metal, metal screen, and metal foam.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Common sheet metals for shielding include copper, brass, nickel, silver, steel, and tin.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Shielding effectiveness, that is, how well a shield reflects or absorbs/suppresses electromagnetic radiation, is affected by the physical properties of the metal.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] These may include conductivity, solderability, permeability, thickness, and weight.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] A metal's properties are an important consideration in material selection.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] For example, electrically dominant waves are reflected by highly conductive metals like copper, silver, and brass, while magnetically dominant waves are absorbed/suppressed by a less conductive metal such as steel or stainless steel.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Further, any holes in the shield or mesh must be significantly smaller than the wavelength of the radiation that is being kept out, or the enclosure will not effectively approximate an unbroken conducting surface.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Another commonly used shielding method, especially with electronic goods housed in plastic enclosures, is to coat the inside of the enclosure with a metallic ink or similar material.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The ink consists of a carrier material loaded with a suitable metal, typically copper or nickel, in the form of very small particulates.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] It is sprayed on to the enclosure and, once dry, produces a continuous conductive layer of metal, which can be electrically connected to the chassis ground of the equipment, thus providing effective shielding.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic shielding is the process of lowering the electromagnetic field in an area by barricading it with conductive or magnetic material.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Copper is used for radio frequency (RF) shielding because it absorbs radio and other electromagnetic waves.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Properly designed and constructed RF shielding enclosures satisfy most RF shielding needs, from computer and electrical switching rooms to hospital CAT-scan and MRI facilities.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] EMI (electromagnetic interference) shielding is of great research interest and several new types of nanocomposites made of ferrites, polymers, and 2D materials are being developed to obtain more efficient RF/microwave-absorbing materials (MAMs).
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] EMI shielding is often achieved by electroless plating of copper as most popular plastics are non-conductive or by special conductive paint.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] One example is a shielded cable, which has electromagnetic shielding in the form of a wire mesh surrounding an inner core conductor.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The shielding impedes the escape of any signal from the core conductor, and also prevents signals from being added to the core conductor.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Some cables have two separate coaxial screens, one connected at both ends, the other at one end only, to maximize shielding of both electromagnetic and electrostatic fields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The door of a microwave oven has a screen built into the window.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] From the perspective of microwaves (with wavelengths of 12 cm) this screen finishes a Faraday cage formed by the oven's metal housing.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Visible light, with wavelengths ranging between 400 nm and 700 nm, passes easily through the screen holes.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] RF shielding is also used to prevent access to data stored on RFID chips embedded in various devices, such as biometric passports.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] NATO specifies electromagnetic shielding for computers and keyboards to prevent passive monitoring of keyboard emissions that would allow passwords to be captured; consumer keyboards do not offer this protection primarily because of the prohibitive cost.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] RF shielding is also used to protect medical and laboratory equipment to provide protection against interfering signals, including AM, FM, TV, emergency services, dispatch, pagers, ESMR, cellular, and PCS.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] It can also be used to protect the equipment at the AM, FM or TV broadcast facilities.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Another example of the practical use of electromagnetic shielding would be defense applications.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] As technology improves, so does the susceptibility to various types of nefarious electromagnetic interference.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The idea of encasing a cable inside a grounded conductive barrier can provide mitigation to these risks.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Electromagnetic radiation consists of coupled electric and magnetic fields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The electric field produces forces on the charge carriers (i.e., electrons) within the conductor.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] As soon as an electric field is applied to the surface of an ideal conductor, it induces a current that causes displacement of charge inside the conductor that cancels the applied field inside, at which point the current stops.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Similarly, *varying* magnetic fields generate eddy currents that act to cancel the applied magnetic field.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] (The conductor does not respond to static magnetic fields unless the conductor is moving relative to the magnetic field.) The result is that electromagnetic radiation is reflected from the surface of the conductor: internal fields stay inside, and external fields stay outside.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Several factors serve to limit the shielding capability of real RF shields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] One is that, due to the electrical resistance of the conductor, the excited field does not completely cancel the incident field.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Also, most conductors exhibit a ferromagnetic response to low-frequency magnetic fields, so that such fields are not fully attenuated by the conductor.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Any holes in the shield force current to flow around them, so that fields passing through the holes do not excite opposing electromagnetic fields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] These effects reduce the field-reflecting capability of the shield.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] This is one aspect of a greater phenomenon called the skin effect.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] A measure of the depth to which radiation can penetrate the shield is the so-called skin depth.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Equipment sometimes requires isolation from external magnetic fields.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] For static or slowly varying magnetic fields (below about 100 kHz) the Faraday shielding described above is ineffective.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] In these cases shields made of high magnetic permeability metal alloys can be used, such as sheets of permalloy and mu-metal or with nanocrystalline grain structure ferromagnetic metal coatings.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] These materials do not block the magnetic field, as with electric shielding, but rather draw the field into themselves, providing a path for the magnetic field lines around the shielded volume.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The best shape for magnetic shields is thus a closed container surrounding the shielded volume.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] The effectiveness of this type of shielding depends on the material's permeability, which generally drops off at both very low magnetic field strengths and high field strengths where the material becomes saturated.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Therefore, to achieve low residual fields, magnetic shields often consist of several enclosures, one inside the other, each of which successively reduces the field inside it.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Entry holes within shielding surfaces may degrade their performance significantly.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Because of the above limitations of passive shielding, an alternative used with static or low-frequency fields is active shielding, in which a field created by electromagnets cancels the ambient field within a volume.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Solenoids and Helmholtz coils are types of coils that can be used for this purpose, as well as more complex wire patterns designed using methods adapted from those used in coil design for magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Active shields may also be designed accounting for the electromagnetic coupling with passive shields, referred to as *hybrid* shielding, so that there is broadband shielding from the passive shield and additional cancellation of specific components using the active system.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Additionally, superconducting materials can expel magnetic fields via the Meissner effect.
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Suppose that we have a spherical shell of a (linear and isotropic) diamagnetic material with relative permeability $\mu _{\text{r}}$ , with inner radius a and outer radius b .
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] Notice that this coefficient appropriately goes to 1 (no shielding) in the limit that $\mu _{\text{r}}\to 1$ .
[src:emi-filtering/electromagnetic-shielding] In the limit that $\mu _{\text{r}}\to \infty$ this coefficient goes to 0 (perfect shielding).
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] A **ferrite bead** – also called a **ferrite block**, **ferrite core**, **ferrite ring**, **EMI filter**, or **ferrite choke** – is a type of choke that suppresses high-frequency electronic noise in electronic circuits.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads employ high-frequency current dissipation in a ferrite ceramic to build high-frequency noise suppression devices.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads prevent electromagnetic interference (EMI) in two directions: *from* a device or *to* a device.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] A conductive cable acts as an antenna – if the device produces radio-frequency energy, this can be *transmitted* through the cable, which acts as an unintentional radiator.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] In this case, the bead is required for regulatory compliance to reduce EMI.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Conversely, if there are other sources of EMI, such as household appliances, the bead prevents the cable from acting as an antenna and *receiving* interference from these other devices.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] This is particularly common on data cables and medical equipment.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Large ferrite beads are commonly seen on external cabling.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] In addition, various smaller ferrite beads are used internally in circuits—on conductors or around the pins of small circuit-board components, such as transistors, connectors, and integrated circuits.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Beads can block low-level unintended radio frequency energy on wires intended to be DC conductors by acting as a low-pass filter.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] For example, on unbalanced coax transmission lines (such as video cables), the cable is designed to contain the signal, and beads can be used to block stray common mode current from using the cable as an antenna while not interfering with the signal carried inside the cable.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] In this use, the bead is a simple form of a balun.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are one of the simplest and least expensive interference filters to install on preexisting electronic cabling.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] For a simple ferrite ring, the wire is wrapped around the core through the center, typically five or seven times.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Clamp-on cores are also available, which attach without wrapping the wire: this type of ferrite core is usually designed so that the wire passes only once through it.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] If the fit is not snug enough, the core can be secured with cable ties, or if the center is large enough, the cabling can loop through one or more times.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] (However, although each loop increases the impedance to high frequencies, it also shifts the frequency of the highest impedance to a lower frequency.) Small ferrite beads can be slipped over component leads to suppress parasitic oscillation.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Surface-mount ferrite beads are available.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Like any other surface-mount inductor, these are soldered into a gap in the printed circuit board trace.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Inside the bead component, a coil of wire runs between layers of ferrite to form a multi-turn inductor around the high-permeability core.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are used as a passive low-pass filter by dissipating radio frequency (RF) energy as heat by design.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors, on the other hand, have no resistance and hence do not dissipate energy as heat.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors only have inductive reactance, which reduces the flow of high-frequency signals by returning some of their energy back towards the signal source (possibly reducing the amount of power drawn) rather than dissipating that energy as heat (as done by the resistance in ferrite beads).
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] While an inductor's reactance may commonly be referred to simply as *impedance*, impedance generally can be any combination of resistance and reactance.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] The geometry and electromagnetic properties of coiled wire over the ferrite bead result in an impedance for high-frequency signals, attenuating high-frequency EMI/RFI electronic noise.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] The energy is either reflected back up the cable or dissipated as low-level heat.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Only in extreme cases is the heat noticeable.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] A ferrite bead can be added to an inductor to improve, in two ways, its ability to block unwanted high frequency noise.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] First, the ferrite concentrates the magnetic field, increasing inductance and, therefore, reactance, which filters out the noise.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Second, if the ferrite is so designed, it can produce an additional loss in the form of resistance in the ferrite itself.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] The ferrite creates an inductor with a very low Q factor.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] This loss heats the ferrite, generally by a negligible amount.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] While the signal level is large enough to cause interference or undesirable effects in sensitive circuits, the energy blocked is typically relatively small.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Depending on the application, the resistive loss characteristic of the ferrite may or may not be desired.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] A design that uses a ferrite bead to improve noise filtering must consider specific circuit characteristics and the frequency range to block.
[src:emi-filtering/ferrite-bead] Different ferrite materials have different properties concerning frequency, and the manufacturer's literature helps select the most effective material for the frequency range.
[src:emi-filtering/line-filter] **EMC filter**, **EMI filter**, **RFI filter**) is an electronic filter that is placed between the mains electricity input and internal circuitry of electronic equipment to attenuate conducted radio frequencies radio frequency interference (RFI), also known as electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:emi-filtering/line-filter] Often it is either integrated into the power entry module or as a separate module (similar to the photo).
